THE MORNING AND NIGHT DEWâTHE TEREE-FEOIDEâWATER-SPOUTS AND WHIRLWINDS â THE BAEBAKY FIG - TEEES â THE CACTUS PLANTSâTHE VIZNAGAâCUE HOPES DISAPPOINTEDâDON BENITO COYOTEPEC. ^"^HE sun had not risen when we were up and ready to start. â ^'kS We shivered with cold, for on the great plateau which ^*-^^ we had now reached, to which the inhabitants of the lower regions give the name of Terre-Froide, the mornings are frosty. The profound darkness was succeeded by a dim twilight, afterwards by a fog, which penetrated our clothing as much as rain. "There has been no shower, " cried Lucien, "and yet we are all wet.".
